Good night, GM tomorrow!  Have you ever watched a product launch so iconic it reshaped the entire industry?  Think of Steve Jobs unveiling the iPhone the moment felt like magic, not just because it was a phone, but because it set a new standard for user expectations.  That‚Äôs what @LABtrade_ recent surge in adoption feels like. The team shared they added 50,000+ new users in just one week.   That surge wasn‚Äôt just numbers it was momentum. Momentum that says: This terminal isn‚Äôt just a tool, it‚Äôs a movement.  Here‚Äôs why it matters to me:  ‚Üí As someone sharing Web3 insights daily, velocity matters. I don‚Äôt want tools that feel stale or niche.  ‚Üí When a platform attracts tens of thousands of users quickly, it means infrastructure is sticking and stories are spreading.  ‚Üí It‚Äôs not hype to say we might be witnessing the iPhone moment of on-chain trading terminals.  Why?  Because expanding mindshare like this sparks network effects: ‚Üí More user-generated strategies in discussions. ‚Üí Referral loops fueling organic awareness. ‚Üí Institutional interest waking up to serious traction.  Personally, I‚Äôve felt it in Telegram groups and mentions discussions are moving faster, use cases multiplying, and the terminal has that everyone‚Äôs talking about it energy.  That‚Äôs powerful.  It doesn‚Äôt guarantee performance but it guarantees relevance.  Steve Jobs didn‚Äôt just sell phones. He shifted expectations.  LAB may not be reinventing hardware, but it‚Äôs redefining what a multichain terminal can be one built around speed, precision, and now, explosive collective adoption.  If adoption is the engine, execution is the fuel. And right now, both are roaring.

Tonight with Alex Goroshko  Neoborn Caveman sits down with Alex Goroshko from Big Sexy for a relaxed chat about making real music in a digital world.  https://t.co/hFO4QomJkI  From their debut River of Shame to the heartfelt single Michigan, Alex shares how Big Sexy stays authentic, with Gary Maccagnone‚Äôs poetic lyrics sparking raw demos across continents. They discuss dodging industry pressures, balancing lyrics and music, and finding a sound that screams ‚ÄúBig Sexy.‚Äù Trading influences like Richie Kotzen‚Äôs raw trio and USSR‚Äôs outlawed Second Breath, they celebrate music‚Äôs power to heal and connect. It‚Äôs a candid talk on resilience, creative freedom, and keeping songs human‚Äîno hype, just heart.  Key Takeaways  Authenticity Matters: Staying true connects with fans, but social media‚Äôs pressure to conform is a double-edged sword.  Digital Hurdles: Independent artists face challenges with fake streams and navigating distribution platforms.  Global Teamwork: Tech lets Big Sexy blend Gary‚Äôs lyrics and Alex‚Äôs riffs from Canada to beyond, creating soulful sounds.  Creative Balance: Lyrics and music compete, but finding the song‚Äôs core voice is key to Big Sexy‚Äôs process.  Music Heals: Alex‚Äôs journey shows how music‚Äôs therapeutic power fuels resilience amid industry changes.  Soundbites  ‚ÄúAuthenticity is the most important thing in music‚Äînot translated into TikTok videos, but it‚Äôs key.‚Äù ‚Äì NC on realness.  ‚ÄúWe create stories and put ourselves in lyrics and music‚Äîsomething we love.‚Äù ‚Äì Alex on the process.  ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs terrifying for most to be authentic‚Äîthat‚Äôs where the magic happens.‚Äù ‚Äì NC on industry truth.  ‚ÄúRichie Kotzen blew me away‚Äîpowerful trio at 22, recording everything himself.‚Äù ‚Äì Alex on influences.  ‚ÄúWe need the whole story‚ÄîI want the journey, not just a snippet.‚Äù ‚Äì NC on albums.
